# One of the languages that AutoKitteh supports is Starlark.
# Although Starlark is a dialect of Python, it is not identical.
# A summary of the differenced is nicely summarized in
# https://github.com/google/starlark-go/blob/master/doc/spec.md#dialect-differences.

# An AutoKitteh program is ran whenever an event is received from
# any of its configured event sources. In the LitterBox, however,
# it runs whenever any event is received.

# Here we load the `event` variable from the `ak` module. The `ak` module
# is a builtin module in AutoKitteh that supplies some common
# functions and variables.
# The `event` variable always contains details about the event
# that triggered this invocation.
load("ak", "event")


# As you can see in the event editor, a 'what' field is specified.
# Let's use it.
what = event.data['what'] or 'world'

# Now we just print a greeting using the above value.
print("meow, %s!" % what)

# To run this, hit "Send" below.
# You'll see the greeting emitted in the console window.
# A link to a low level description of how the event
# is processed will also appear next to the Event editor.

# Now try to change the "what" field value below, and hit "Send" again.
# Convince yourself that the value sent is the one used :)

# Also note that if you want to change the program, you'll need to
# hit "Update".

# Below are embedded event examples. The litterbox knows to parse
# these lines and populate the "Events" section below.
# EVENT meow: { "src": "someone", "type": "greeting", "data": { "what": { "string": { "v": "world" } } } }
